metadata.name: DIGITAL DISOBEDIENCE #290
metadata.description:
As artists, we believe it is our duty to use our skills to comment on the state of the world and the pressing issues facing humanity. Through our art, we aim to pre-empt the future and explore the potential consequences of our current actions. We use symmetry as a visual metaphor for the balance we must strive for in society, particularly in regards to human rights and the treatment of marginalized groups. In the age of technology and AI advancements, it is more important than ever to consider the impact these developments may have on our world and the diverse individuals and communities that inhabit it. Our work serves as a reminder that we must take responsibility for our actions and work towards creating a more just and equitable future for all.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

metadata.name: Separation in the Night #155
metadata.description:
For this project I was strongly inspired by the paintings of Mark Rothko, Jackson Pollock, Kazemir Malevich, but mostly token refers to the works of one of the largest figures of the European avant-garde, Paul Klee. I wanted to convey that complex color mood and atmosphere that artist achieved with oil paints. 
I have been working with color palettes and functions for a long time to make complex transitions and gradients. This code has really huge potential for a wide diversity of artworks and I would like to see as many interesting variations as possible. Enjoy<3

Project contains:

•three canvas types : horizontal, vertical, square
•rare features : vertical stripes, posterization
•press "p" to pause animation and play again
•open in tab and press "s" to save .png


Made in P5.js by @Georginerous

metadata.name: Unit of me #27
metadata.description:
Just like a river, which is always flowing and changing, we are never the same from one moment to the next. Our individuality is composed of countless fragments, each with its unique size and color, that come together to form who we are at any given moment. These fragments constantly shift, some become more prominent and vibrant, while others fade into the background. We are constantly being molded and shaped by the passage of time, so that who we are today is not who we were yesterday, and will not be who we are tomorrow

13 color palettes
3 canvas proportion ratio
and more 3 different traits

Press S to save a .png

Created by Zamboni
Dec. 2022

metadata.name: Psilocybe Azurescens #17
metadata.description:
Psilocybe Azurescens is a generative algorithm that draws a very potent psychedelic fungus. The Azurescens species occurs naturally along a small area of the West Coast of the United States, including in parts of Oregon and California.  The mushroom has an affinity for coastal dune grasses.

The halftone hatching patterns and 3d mushroom geometries are all unique and driven by fx features and the transaction hash.  

- Double click to enable turntable mode
- Click or touch and drag to rotate in 3D, scroll or pinch to zoom
- Don’t eat too many of these super funky boomerangs off-chain - they are strong!

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

metadata.name: CSS Molecules #212
metadata.description:
This 3d animated work is composed almost completely of HTML + CSS. There is a limited amount of javascript to construct the scene and facilitate interactive controls. 🚫 <canvas>!

A bit of history about this approach: As my first coding language HTML and CSS holds a special place in my heart. Even when I jumped into 3D my first creations were made with just some html + css coded in notepad. Earlier this year I took this idea to the next level with a yet-to-be-released 3D bedrooms project, filling it with objects and ever-refining my scene construction practice. This system for scene construction became the basis for a few other generative projects here on fxhash under my pseudonym htmlcss.tez. Here I abandon my usual representational focus with this technique and dive right into the abstract.

metadata.name: Maze #35
metadata.description:
Made with Magicavoxel size 2048 x 2048

A maze is a puzzle with twists and turns, where you try to find a path from the entrance to the exit without hitting dead ends. You can walk through a maze. The goal of a maze is to get through it, which means going the wrong way, retracing your steps, and choosing different paths.

metadata.name: Minimal Monoliths #64
metadata.description:
Minimal Monoliths is a work mainly inspired by the use of AI as a creative tool.  I have a new fixation with monoliths as simple minimal structures just placed on random surfaces, so I iterated quite a few illustrations to sense the variations of shapes. 

Once I had an idea of what I wanted, I translated it into code creating something minimal with very fine lines that flow and then at some random point are disrupted by an emerging element.

Then in order to add volume and create a sense of depth, I increased the number of lines per iteration.

As Monoliths are considered elements deeply connected with nature I wanted to keep the lines and backgrounds within the spectrum of the earth's colors.

9 Color Palettes 
4 Backgrounds
Lines count [23,31,41,59,67,79,89,97,109] 

Made with ❤️ & pj5s

By CodeNFT (Clementine Novak)
October 2022

metadata.name: Richter #316
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/
fxhash.xyz/generative/17030/
